# Security and Hardening

## When to use

- Handling user input, auth, or session state
- Storing PII, payment data, or secrets
- Adding a third-party dependency or external integration
- Building anything reachable from the public internet

## Process

1. Threat-model first: list trust boundaries, assets, and abuse cases
2. Three-tier boundaries: untrusted edge → validated core → trusted internals
3. Validate input with allowlists at the edge, never with denylists
4. Parameterize queries, encode output, set security headers
5. Hash passwords with bcrypt/argon2; rotate and scope secrets
6. Run dependency audit on every change

## Rationalizations to ignore

| Lie you tell yourself | Why it's wrong |
|---|---|
| It's an internal tool, threat-modelling is overkill. | Internal tools become external one merge later. Model now. |
| We trust our database, no need to parameterize. | Trust the layer; parameterize anyway. Defense in depth costs nothing. |
| This dependency is fine, npm audit is too noisy. | Audit, then suppress with reason. Silent suppression hides supply-chain attacks. |

## Red flags

- Raw SQL string concatenation with user input
- Password stored or logged in plaintext
- CORS set to wildcard with credentials
- Secret committed to git history
- Third-party dependency with no lockfile pin
- User input flowing to eval/shell/HTML without escaping

## Verification

- Threat model recorded for the changed surface
- npm audit / pip-audit / cargo audit exit 0 (or risks documented)
- OWASP Top 10 checklist reviewed for relevant items
